China lacks tourists.
Beijing is losing billions because of visa policy.
For decades, China has been trying to use its influence without the use of force.
It spends $ 10 billion a year to support language schools and build universities abroad, pushing its entertainment industry to foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.
But Beijing is failing.
The local state media talks about a plan to make tourism a driving force for economic change and modernization.
However, the number of arrivals increased by only 3.8 percent last year, and about 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that, despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, the situation in the world&#39;s most populous country is assessed by Christopher Balding, an economics professor at the University of Beijing, in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for itself is China&#39;s visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free travel with China, and the citizens of the others have to obtain a visa in advance.
At the Chinese authorities in the USA, therefore, the crowds are comparable to the Chinese New Year celebrations.
A visa costs $ 140, but if you don&#39;t want to wait long hours in line, you have to pay $ 100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic barriers.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces a country&#39;s number of visitors by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while 1.8 million Americans visited Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China&#39;s gross domestic product and less than one percent of the population.
China often exacerbates this problem when using tourism to achieve its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China cut traffic to South Korea in the spring as part of a rift over South Korea&#39;s anti-missile system, South Koreans repaid it and avoided China.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year on year, while Japan recorded an increase of 85 percent.
All this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recent report by the US Federal Reserve, China could leave as much as $ 190 billion as a result of Chinese travel abroad, while China earns about $ 35 billion a year to sell currency to incoming tourists.
According to official balance of payments figures, China had a $ 217 billion tourism deficit last year, equivalent to 44 percent of China&#39;s total trade surplus in goods.
Thus, a small number of tourists deal a very painful blow to a country that anxiously prevents the outflow of capital.
However, the above-mentioned factors are only one manifestation of more general restraint towards foreigners.
In many parts of China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, less than a million foreigners lived in China.
Some individual cities in the United States have more.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has doubled.
A number of scientific studies show that immigrants tend to boost economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
However, you can hardly find them in China.
Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step that is being offered is visa facilitation.
Other Asian countries, notably India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and reduce the cost of visa procedures.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currencies, it should be easier for them to get there.
