How the financial rules of football will affect Neymar&#39;s move to Paris
Rules restricting the funding of European football clubs will not disrupt Neymar&#39;s record-breaking transfer from Barcelona, Spain, to Paris-Saint Germain, France.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by the EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
The Financial Fair Play (FFP) rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 stipulate that the PSG will have to prove that Neymar&#39;s transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona has paid EUR 222 million just to buy Neymar out of his contract, and Neymar will demand a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
The following are some of the financial terms of Neymar&#39;s transfer to France.
Given that the PSG team is funded by a wealthy Qatari family who have become rich in energy sales, they can afford to bring Neymar into an already stellar football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums on players to buy, but on the other hand, they have to prove legal sources of income, which allows them to cover the overhead costs of football-related business activities.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after being appointed UEFA Director in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs in debt in the pursuit of new reinforcements would ultimately cheat and risk bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, the FFP&#39;s rules shifted its focus from club debt to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spend huge sums on players and to build a global brand - was suddenly not so advantageous.
Under the current three-year trial period, which ends in 2018, clubs can report a loss of up to € 30 million.
And despite Platini having to leave his post in 2015, his successor, Alexander Cheferin, is determined to defend the ban on over-spending.
&quot;The FFP rules still apply, and we are determined to strengthen them in the future,&quot; Andrea Traverso, who oversees compliance with the FFP rules, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid the amount for the redemption of Neymar in a lump sum payment, it can spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract for accounting purposes.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down to EUR 44.4 million annually for five years.
The first wave of FFP&#39;s highest sanctions hit PSG in 2014, along with Manchester City, which is owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG was fined € 60 million ($ 82 million) - which was later reduced to € 20 million - and ordered to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is wary of teams that may try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their revenues through affiliated club owners.
Thus, even if the Qatari company sponsors PSG as soon as the financing exceeds the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the billing of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after deciding that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
According to some reports, part of Neymar&#39;s income in the PSG could be paid from the organizing committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
However, PSG and officials of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar denied the fat that Neymat should become the ambassador of the World Cup in football and that such a maneuver would be easily detected by UEFY officials.
Previous sanctions imposed on the PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
According to an insider&#39;s statement on Tuesday, UEFA did not open any investigation into the transfer of Neymar to PSG.
The source of this report wanted to remain anonymous, as he is not entitled to comment on the situation with PSG, the Associated Press reported.
The latest published financial statements show that PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of EUR 10 million and a turnover of EUR 542.4 million.
The financial statements for the current financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects the arrival of Neymar to be a huge opportunity for sponsors, merchandising and jersey sales.
The club promises to increase turnover by up to 30 percent from signing the contract.
Officials in the Spanish league, apparently concerned about the departure of one of the biggest stars, sought to thwart Neymar&#39;s departure, arguing that the PSG would violate FFP rules.
&quot;This is a clear case of &#39;financial doping&#39; for both the club and the state,&quot; La Liga President Javier Teba told AS Spanish newspaper, referring to the PSG club&#39;s ownership of the Qatari syndicate.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports mogul, shares La Liga&#39;s same view of the club&#39;s funding.
&quot;It&#39;s a result of ownership that has fundamentally changed the football world in the last 15 years,&quot; Wenger said on Thursday.
