An entrepreneur is to serve ten years for an extreme tax evasion.
The Constitutional Court rejected the complaint of the businessman Jiří Toman, who is to serve a significant ten years in prison for cutting taxes.
The calculated damage is 645 million crowns.
In his complaint, Toman claimed that the judiciary had violated his fundamental rights, and that the factual findings of the courts in Zlín and Olomouc were allegedly incomplete.
However, the constitutional judges called the complaint unfounded, ČTK found out from the court&#39;s database.
ÚS is not another court of appeal.
&quot;It cannot, as a fourth instance, consider factual or legal errors allegedly committed by ordinary courts, unless they constitute a violation of constitutionally protected rights and freedoms,&quot; the resolution states.
Toman was judged to have fled.
The verdict has been valid since November 2015, when it was confirmed by the High Court in Olomouc.
At that time, Toman was in custody in Argentina, where, according to the resolution, he was also at the time of the decision-making process.
The penalty imposed is at the upper limit of the statutory rate, which according to the verdict corresponds to the damage incurred.
The High Court described the case as an extreme tax evasion that has a macroeconomic impact on the state budget.
From 2005 to 2008, the man served as Chairman of the Board of Directors of World Servis.
The damage of 645 million crowns occurred only in the period from January to July 2008, the total leakage, according to the expert, exceeded one billion.
However, for procedural reasons, it was no longer possible to try Toman for the full amount.
According to the indictment, World Servis did not include all invoices in its tax returns.
Instead of monthly VAT and excise tax payments in the order of at least tens of millions of crowns, taxes were paid in only hundreds of thousands.
World Servis and some of the companies with which the company traded have a relationship with the entrepreneur Radomír Vybíral, to whom the judiciary imposed 13 years in prison for VAT machinations in fuel trades.
His complaint was also rejected some time ago by the Constitutional Court.
