The NHS prescribes a controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
From September, patients will gain access to &#39;transformative&#39; HIV prevention treatment based on the Supreme Court&#39;s decision to fund the NHS.
The English National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-sex prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients in a three-year trial times.
NSH agreed to fund a probationary period after the Court of Appeal upheld a decision by the Supreme Court last year stating that the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP, despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was taken by NHS England from CEO Simon Stevens as a &#39;significant intervention&#39;, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a &#39;decisive moment&#39;.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Additional clinics will join in October and will be fully implemented across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
PrEP pre-sex application means that there are enough specific drugs in the patient&#39;s body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include homosexual or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will designate eligible participants who will sign a consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also sign up at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential testing.
The program will cost taxpayers £ 10 million and the NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute the drugs after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use, and large-scale implementation.
Simon Stevens added: &#39;This important intervention should complement and fully exploit the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than thirty years of efforts to halt one of the greatest challenges to human health. &#39;
Deborah Gold, executive director of the NAT (National AIDS Trust), said: &#39;We are witnessing a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP is given the opportunity to transform the English HIV epidemic if given correctly and at risk for patients.
From September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will improve the quality of many lives.
We welcome this statement. &#39;
Ian Green, CEO of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: &#39;The number one priority must be to rapidly deploy tests across the country; we must ensure that it is available to every patient.
We now have the trial drug PrEP and are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV. &#39;
Shadow Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: &#39;The start of the PrEP trial is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug may be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV, and together to stop the spread of HIV in society. &#39;
Living on a high footing: the mezzanine and clever design have turned this small apartment on Earls Court into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, replaced a large house in Knightsbridge in 2014 with an apartment on Earls Cour.
Located on the first floor of the clever Queen Anne Terrace - it is a demonstration of modern design that makes the most of the space available.
&quot;I used to live with my ex-husband in a much bigger house in Knightsbridge,&quot; Joanne said.
&quot;I was looking for something for a more reasonable price.
I came across this apartment in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I fell in love with him right away and nodded at him the same day. &quot;
Since then, the 1000 square meter apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
One-bedroom apartment with a complicated layout - you had to go through the kitchen to get to the bedroom - Joanne wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine to use the high ceiling.
&quot;I longed for a high ceiling, large windows and lots of light.
Those were my demands, &quot;she said.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi of Notting Hill-based Duck &amp; Shed and used a nearly four-foot ceiling to create a home that was not just a project, but also a place to live.
The ceiling did not reach such a height that two gaps could fit on top of each other - the challenge for the architects was to create a mezzanine floor on which to walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
&quot;The steel structure is quite complicated,&quot; he explained.
&quot;We had to arrange both spaces so that we could walk upright.
It was not just a matter of building a simple platform, but also of bending the steel structure so that it was at the right height above and below the ceiling. ”
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - while adding to the drama.
On the mezzanine floor, old copper window frames in the Retrouvius design overlook the beautiful living room.
The mirrored furniture in gold color, silver lines and retro chandelier Serge Mouille create a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor has mirrors on both sides, making it look longer.
The mirror bar in the kitchen looks like a window to another room.
At the front door there are storage rooms equipped with mirrors for storing cutlery and glasses.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of a significantly larger space, is the possibility of separating it from the kitchen if it is not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
However, what is unique about this solution is the folding door.
&quot;We had to solve the technical side,&quot; Erfan says of the reinforced veneered door.
&quot;The door has a counterweight to make it very easy to roll.&quot;
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage space, Joanne gained another 16 square meters, a second room and a better overall layout of the apartment.
&quot;When it comes down to it, what you&#39;re selling is living space - or valuing your property,&quot; Erfan said.
&quot;A real estate agent basically calculates his price when entering an apartment based on his living space.&quot;
In this case, we managed to increase the living space while maintaining quality materials that give the space a luxurious look.
&quot;The material is very important because you touch it and form an emotional bond with home,&quot; Erfan added.
&quot;You won&#39;t fall in love with the electrical wiring in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but your hearts will not win. ”
As it turned out, a quality design and an increase in living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional work.
And like Joanne, you may eventually decide to stay.
The United States is breaking up.
The cultural and political gap between the blue and red states is widening.
California has banned its citizens from traveling to Tennessee and seven other states.
The state of Tennessee retaliated and declared a retaliatory ban on its citizens traveling to California.
Of course, this is not a ban in the full sense of the word, US citizens can travel freely in all fifty states.
The point is that California has banned state money from traveling on its citizens to eight other states, such as Alabama, South Dakota, Kansas, Kentucky, Mississippi, North Carolina, Tennessee and Texas.
Who will stop this madness?
California is strongly in favor of LGBT and considers any expression of disagreement with the LGBT lifestyle to be discrimination.
However, Tennessee has passed a conscientious objection law that states that a psychotherapist who has a moral problem with LGBT patients has no obligation to provide it to them, but has a duty to provide those patients with another therapist who does not have such a problem.
Texas and other states have passed laws under which religious charities that have given mothers children after birth for adoption are not required to provide those children for adoption to same-sex couples.
Because of these conscientious objection laws, California has banned funding for its citizens&#39; travel to eight states.
In practice, this means that California professors must not be reimbursed by their universities for scientific symposia in Texas, for example, because they are co-financed by the State of California.
Similarly, school sports teams cannot travel to tournaments or competitions, for example, to Tennessee with the financial support of their schools.
They have to get either federal grants to travel, but it is absurd for the federal government to fund citizens&#39; trips from state A to state B, or private sponsorship.
The state of Tennessee has run out of patience and its parliament passed a resolution stating that it also dislikes California&#39;s policy of high taxes, high government spending, high deficits and tolerance of illegal immigrants, but still does not impose a travel embargo on California.
He imposes them in retaliation for the California travel embargo on Tennessee.
And the same will happen to any state in the Union that would impose a similar travel ban on another state for any reason.
At the same time, he called on the parliaments of all states to stop this madness.
That&#39;s the facts, now the comment.
The situation is toxic.
First, all of it is constitutional, nothing is unconstitutional.
States have the right to pass conscientious objection laws, as well as decide what their money will go to and what they must not.
Second, what&#39;s wrong with conscience?
If a butcher has a religious problem selling pork, why can&#39;t he just offer beef, lamb, poultry and fish?
Why, under penalty of punishment, force him to sell pork when there are enough butchers offering pork?
In Colorado, a baker faces an anti-discrimination lawsuit and a heavy fine for refusing to bake a cake for a gay wedding.
But he also refuses to bake cakes for Halloween or containing alcohol.
Why punish him and leave him alone and not order the appropriate cakes from hundreds of other bakers?
Third, the beauty of the federal system is that the constitutional rights of all citizens of the federation are guaranteed, but individual states can adjust their domestic, domestic policies in non-federal powers according to their own, ie, the preferences of their citizens.
Then there is diversity, diversity, diversity.
California can be California and Texas can be Texas.
But California wants California to be California and Texas and seven other states to be California too!
Fourth, members of the LGBT community once legitimately sought tolerance for their lifestyle.
Today, many members of this community follow the rule of live and let live, which should be followed by all reasonable people, but some activists strive not for tolerance of themselves and others, but for extreme intolerance of others.
According to them, no one should ever again show moral, religious or philosophical disagreement with the LGBT lifestyle, and if they do, they should be criminalized.
The mentality of these activists is totalitarian.
They are the modern enemies of freedom.
Fifth, I do not know the situation in American history, where states deliberately did so on political issues, except for one case.
Even in times of struggle for the civil rights of blacks, where the North and West were on the side of integration and the South on the side of segregation, states did not impose sanctions on themselves.
The only case was the 1950s, the political cause was slavery and the North was fighting against the South.
Of course, nothing like that will happen now, but the situation is still toxic.
The cultural and political gap between the Blue Democratic States and the Red Republican States is widening and the United States is mentally disintegrating internally.
