In the center of one of the rooms in New York&#39;s Fridman Gallery are several faces of different skin tones - white, black and brown - hung from the ceiling on wires. Each of them seemed to fall out of sight of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized publication of secret cablegrams on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which began on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience with technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he left the US presidency.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning&#39;s DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on the pliability of DNA - as well as the many ways DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these. interpretations as well as identities.
Born Bradley Edward Manning, Manning has said since she was a woman that she considered herself a woman. She was convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including violations of six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All her photographs were held by prison staff. Only one lower-quality black-and-white photograph leaked to the public, in which Manning, visibly worried, is sitting in the driver&#39;s seat in the platinum-blonde wig she is now associated with.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to the Dewey-Hagborg project from 2012 Stranger Visions.
