Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the level of employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but did not find a suitable survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And despite promising anonymity to the survey, some employees expressed distrust in the whole process.
&quot;I was looking for consistency and objectivity,&quot; said Errett, owner of the San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
So she asked for help from outside.
New startups in the field of human resources are constantly appearing on the market, which help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intent of measuring employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to vote quickly, target specific teams and demographics, offer complete employee anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass superiors and contact directors directly. .
&quot;There are tools on the market like Diet and Fitbit that monitor your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?&quot; Said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reintwood-based Glint.
