Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can alleviate the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
Red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare for your digestive system.
However, a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 patients in the United Kingdom, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to eat meat and dairy products to alleviate their symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps build immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
Study leader dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the weighing pans are tilted to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
In the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting the tolerance of the body in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to make cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have found a link between one type of bacterium - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the intestinal microbiome and the development of cells that support the body&#39;s tolerance.
The more tryptophan their diets had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had. ”
He also suggested that if the same were shown to be true in humans, then the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory bowel environment.
Postgraduate researcher dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered in a study of a certain type of immune cells supporting body tolerance that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice kept separately lacked cells.
She deduced from this that one group of mice has a different intestinal microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that commonly reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The gut of the mice was tested by DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
Mice that were housed in a sterile environment and lacked an intestinal microbiome — so they did not develop this type of immune cell — were given L. reuteri — and developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells, which were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removal of the active ingredient from the fluid, it has been shown to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of the mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. At the same time, the number of cells dropped by half after halving the doses of tryptophan.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but tryptophan-related gene defects have been found in humans with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: &quot;Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells, because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase cell populations. ”
