The White House props cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House&#39;s decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry last month was $ 24,000, according to Navy records released by TIME.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the culmination of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a showcase of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials watched a display of products from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a fork lift truck from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and requested the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an &quot;emergency&quot;, according to Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1).
&quot;I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant incident,&quot; Commander HMX-1 wrote in an email to his superior, Deputy Chief of the Air Force the day before the incident.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive in South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. on the occasion of the show, which is scheduled to begin at 3 p.m. 00.
The e-mail also stated that if there was a delay in departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for the return flight due to working time regulations.
The original crew remained in place that evening, along with a helicopter and a security unit.
From the records - obtained by the weekly TIME - it was not clear whether the second crew was finally sent.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this Regulation.
&quot;We wondered if it was a violation of the Hatch Act, and we were assured that everything was in order,&quot; the commander wrote.
&quot;Sounds like you&#39;ve been blocked,&quot; the deputy commander replied.
This &quot;Made in America&quot; show was designated an official event by the White House, so the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political overtones.
During his participation in the event, the president promoted the health care reform, which went through the senate, and spoke of the effort to keep government regulations in check.
The use of aircraft such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after a presidential plane flew in the background at his first rally as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is flooded with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
&quot;The White House is pleased with the &#39;Made in America&#39; show, which featured products from all 50 countries made by Americans from American materials,&quot; said Lindsay Walters, the deputy secretary of the press.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington and South Lawn areas and practice possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the crew&#39;s current training, a government official said.
On the same day, the helicopter unit flew another eleven hours as part of &quot;non-presidential support missions&quot;.
The White House said no additional props were paid for taxpayers&#39; money.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was in no way interested in negotiations to display a helicopter on South Lawn.
The HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the show is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017, the reimbursement of DoD expenses for VH-3D is $ 24,380 per flight hour.
The unit&#39;s records show a time of 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of a helicopter are well below that amount.
&quot;It is very misleading to state taxpayers&#39; costs based on cost estimates,&quot; Walters said of the matter.
&quot;These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs, which are included in the annual costs.&quot;
According to the 2015 RAND study, reimbursement of DoD expenses does not include staff costs, but includes fuel costs, maintenance and contract costs.
White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated the use of a helicopter for the show&#39;s purposes.
&quot;The idea of the show, which takes place this week, is to introduce products made in the USA,&quot; said Spicer.
&quot;I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state and that they provide work for hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military facilities that count countless Americans.
It is appropriate to recall this fact. &quot;
It&#39;s not clear if Trump was to look at the helicopter during his tour of South Lawn. The only thing that can be said for sure is that he got behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
&quot;I know Sikorsky very well,&quot; said the president, &quot;I own three myself.&quot;
