The unique brewery brews beer again.
For a good beer in a resurrected brewery.
The enthusiasm and honesty of the new owners brought the brewery in Lobča u Mšen back to life a few years ago.
The brewery, first mentioned in 1586, has a Renaissance core and was rebuilt into steam-engine operation in the nineteenth century.
Years of prosperity followed, when the brewery was famous mainly for dark beers.
Unfortunately, during the Second World War, production was stopped and in 1984 the brewery was nationalized.
Since then, the buildings have served as a state farm.
The work of destruction was completed by the owners of the brewery after 1989.
The abandoned area was devastated and dismantled into building materials.
In 2007, however, new hope shone in the form of new owners, architects Jana and Pavel Prouzový.
They began to repair buildings with maximum respect for the spirit of construction and every detail.
They have been and continue to study archival materials, trying to preserve the original materials and building elements.
The brewery has the same appearance as in the nineteenth century, when its golden era began.
Their work was recognized by the brewery as a cultural monument by the Ministry of Culture, and the building also became part of the European Industrial Heritage Trails.
In 2015, they also ceremoniously renewed the tradition of brewing beer.
If you want to taste great Lobeč beer in the picturesque landscape of the Kokořín region, visit the bar in the brewery complex.
When brewing beer, they use Kokorin water springing in a protected landscape area, malt from Lobeč fields and Satu Mare hops.
